  "prompt": "Why does adenine combine with thymine only and not cytosine?",
  "response": "Adenine (A) combines exclusively with thymine (T) in DNA due to the specific hydrogen bonding and structural compatibility between these bases. The pairing is dictated by the principles of complementary base pairing and the shape and chemistry of the nucleotide structures.\n\n1. **Hydrogen Bonding**: Adenine forms two hydrogen bonds with thymine. Cytosine, on the other hand, forms three hydrogen bonds with guanine (G). The two hydrogen bonds between adenine and thymine contribute to the stability and accuracy of the DNA structure.\n\n2. **Structural Compatibility**: The sizes and shapes of the adenine and thymine molecules allow them to fit together properly in the double helical structure of DNA. Adenine is a purine (a larger, two-ring structure) while thymine is a pyrimidine (a smaller, single-ring structure). Purines and pyrimidines pair together to maintain a uniform width of the DNA helix.\n\n3. **Chemical Properties**: The specific arrangement of atoms and the chemical properties of the bases ensure that adenine and thymine bond together preferentially. The energetic favorability and spatial arrangement of the hydrogen bond donors and acceptors between adenine and thymine make their pairing more stable compared to any alternative pairing.\n\nThese factors are crucial for the fidelity of DNA replication and transcription processes, allowing cells to pass genetic information accurately through generations.",
